text:
2:33:40 Hi Gura, Hi Chumbuddies! I guess I'm the guy who does massive posts answering questions posed in HoloEN Minecraft streams, because it's time for more SCIENCE! (disclaimer- mistakes and generalisation/assumptions may be present.)

Does Minecraft have Ozone? Can a square have a[n] Ozone? Is the minecraft world flat?

Okay, so multiple questions here. Easiest to explain first- The minecraft world isn't 'flat' in the true definition, but it is PLANAR. The Minecraft world is 3 dimensional (it has x y and z planes) however, it has no CURVATURE. To my understanding, Minecraft has a soft 'edge' after which, you hit a wall and can't go further. Chunks still load, so the world continues but we can't travel to it. You can't walk in one direction so far you arrive back at your start point, as in a typical planet. This leads to two possible conclusions, which will change the answers to other questions-
1: The minecraft world is an infinite plane and would continue on forever if you weren't stopped.
2: The minecraft world extends past the traversable boarders, but ends at some point out of sight.

Onto Ozone! I believe Gura is misspeaking here, and referring to a planet's atmosphere rather than specifically about Ozone.
Ozone is the common name for the Oxygen triatom (O3). We have it in our atmosphere, mostly very high up in the 'ozone layer' it's very useful for filtering UV light and solar radiation (amongst other things). Fun fact, Lightning strikes generate ozone on impact with the ground, so if you wanted to smell it, you could run out in a lightning storm (DON'T RUN OUT IN A LIGHTNING STORM.)
Back to the questions, well...let's differentiate. If Gura is talking about an atmosphere, then yes, the Minecraft world does have an atmosphere, and a cubic planet can indeed have one! How do we know this? Well...Minecraft has some amount of physics. We can infer certain properties about the world based on the existing physics.

Gravity - Stuff falls, which implies an amount of gravity. Specifically, Steve/Alex falls.
With gravity present, any air/gasses on the surface can be held in place by gravity, creating the pressure which would form an atmosphere.

Water- exists in the game, and is named specifically water. We can assume, then, that minecraft water, largely, is chemically identical to water as we know it. (The physical properties of minecraft water, such as fluid dynamics and flow, are a little weird, but let's not worry about that.)
Water placed in a vacuum (note- a place with no air/atmosphere, or atmospheric pressure, such as space. Vacuum here does not refer to a hoover, or vacuum cleaner.) will boil, regardless of the temperature of the water. 
Water placed in minecraft will not boil, therefore the minecraft world does NOT exist in a vacuum. If the world is not a vacuum, then there is an atmosphere present.

Equally, the player cannot stay underwater forever. Specifically, the player drowns if they stay underwater too long. This is medically defined (I believe) as flooding of the longs, leading to oxygen starvation of the brain.
We don't know that Steve/Alex breathe oxygen specifically, but the fact that they survive above water, but no below, implies breathing AIR. Breathing air isn't possible without an atmosphere, therefore one must be present.

An interesting physics question: Can a [square] (I assume she means cube) have an atmosphere/ozone- YES! The gravity well of a cube is a little weird, and inconsistent, which would possibly lead to areas of higher/lower atmospheric pressure, but it would not prevent formation of an atmosphere.

Now, onto Ozone. Does Minecraft specifically have OZONE? I would say probably, but not necessarily.
The difficulty here, is we don't know the specific composition of the air and atmosphere of minecraft. If there's no oxygen, there can't possibly be Ozone in amounts sufficient for an Ozone layer. So...is Oxygen present in minecraft...?
Well, almost certainly. How do we know this?
Stuff burns. The process of burning things is actually a chemical reaction, consisting of the ignition of a fuel in the presence of oxygen to release energy (as heat and light) and Carbon Dioxide.
So, since stuff burns, there is sufficient oxygen present in the atmosphere to allow combustion.
As stated earlier, Ozone can be created by lightning strikes, and lightning strikes occur in minecraft therefore...
Ozone can exist in minecraft.
Is there enough of it to form an Ozone layer? I can't say for sure.

TL;DR-
Minecraft world is planar- it has no curvature, and is not a spheroid, but is not technically "flat" as it has 3 definite dimensions.
Can a square have an Ozone? If there is Ozone present on a cubic planet, an ozone layer can form, it will just be a weirder shape than ours on Earth!
Does Minecraft have an Ozone? Maybe! It Absolutely has an atmosphere, and there's no reason the Ozone triatom can't exist on minecraft- there just might not be enough of it to form a whole "layer"

Thanks for reading!

Unofficial HoloEn Youtube science dude.

text:
Try using Left click drag instead of right click drag, for placing items in the crafting grid. You'll like it

Now here's a tip for finding the resource portals.
Nene was nice enough to create a waterway that leads to all of the resource portals.
You can reach it from the EN portal area.
Mesa Road is in the resource 1 portal. It looks like a tower made of glowstone with water in the middle.(It's near the Multicolored building that Polka shot you in.)
Resource 3 is the portal on top of the community center.(It's the portal you used for the Umisea collab)

Ya know, Shion has an Elytra. You should practice using yours so you look cool around her.

While you're at it, check out 
Deep Rock Galactic
It's a great PVE Co-op shooter
It even has interface and subtitle localization, so JP members can enjoy as well.
Rock and Stone!

text:
Nice work on the mansion Gura, it‚Äôs looking really cool overlooking the abandoned Jacksonburg! Always a treat having these long, chill build n talk streams.
You mentioned Bubb4bot earlier, it‚Äôd be awesome if you set one up for laidback stream BGM, even if you use it for your own playlist instead of ours!
As for the carpal tunnel thing, just like with your new chair, you‚Äôll notice a big difference from a few small changes so it‚Äôs definitely worth it. I‚Äôd hate to see you have to take an unwelcome break and go through the same pain some of us did from letting it get bad.
Chat‚Äôs suggestions for adjusting your desk and chair to keep your arms in a better position are the most important thing you can do for ergonomics. Building a wrist stretch habit is equally important, they become second nature to do throughout the day cus they only take like 30 seconds.
Some extra optional suggestions: wrist curls once a day with 1lb weights, a little muscle in your wrists goes a loooong way for preventing pain. A mouse that keeps your hand sideways instead of downwards also helps quite a bit; it takes pressure off the nerves and keeps your tendons closer to their natural resting position. Only worth it if you spend a lot of time on the computer off stream since they‚Äôre pretty bad for gaming, and simply not using the computer will let you rest your wrists the same way.
